from Somalia six months ago and speaks limited English. She has had no antenatal care. She does not take any regular medications and has no significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed with contractions every three minutes. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a term pregnancy with cephalic presentation. External genital examination reveals altered anatomy with fusion of the labia majora leaving only a small posterior opening. A cardiotocograph shows regular contractions and normal fetal heart rate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Female genital mutilation type 4","Female genital mutilation type 3","Female genital mutilation type 1","Female genital mutilation type 2","Labial adhesions"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis woman presents with features consistent with female genital mutilation (FGM) type 3, also known as infibulation. The examination findings of fusion of the labia majora with only a small posterior opening are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Etype 3 FGM\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the most extensive form of FGM and is common in East African countries including Somalia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 1 FGM\u003C/strong\u003E involves partial or total removal of the clitoris and/or prepuce (clitoridectomy) but does not involve fusion of the labia. This would not explain the examination findings in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 FGM\u003C/strong\u003E involves partial or total removal of the clitoris and labia minora, with or without excision of the labia majora, but again does not involve fusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 4 FGM\u003C/strong\u003E includes all other harmful procedures to the female genitalia for non-medical purposes, such as pricking, piercing, incising, scraping, and cauterisation. This would not cause the anatomical changes seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELabial adhesions\u003C/strong\u003E typically occur in pre-pubertal girls due to low oestrogen levels and result in fusion of the labia minora, not the labia majora. They usually separate spontaneously at puberty.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWomen with type 3 FGM require deinfibulation (surgical division of the fusion) to allow for vaginal examination and safe delivery. This should be performed with appropriate counselling, consent, and the assistance of a professional interpreter. Healthcare providers should be aware of the psychological impact of FGM and provide culturally sensitive care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Female genital mutilation type 3 (infibulation) involves narrowing of the vaginal opening through creation of a covering seal by cutting and repositioning the labia minora and/or labia majora.","Women with type 3 FGM require deinfibulation during pregnancy or labour to allow for safe delivery.","Healthcare providers must be culturally sensitive and use professional interpreters when caring for women with FGM."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Female genital mutilation (FGM) [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Jun 23]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Female-Genital-Mutilation.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53551"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16974"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53551"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T09:48:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T09:49:40+10:30"},"relationships